# Git workflow

`main` has admin bypass for emergencies only. **All routine code changes use branches and pull requests.**

## Required flow

1. Branch from up-to-date `main`.
2. Make focused commits on that branch.
3. Push the branch and open a PR on GitHub.
4. **Stop before merge.** The maintainer reviews the PR in the browser and merges manually.
5. Do not push to `main`, squash-merge locally, or merge a PR unless the user explicitly asks.

## Branch naming

Use lowercase, hyphen-separated names with a type prefix:

| Prefix | Use for |
|--------|---------|
| `feat/` | New features or user-visible behavior |
| `fix/` | Bug fixes |
| `chore/` | Tooling, CI, deps, repo hygiene |
| `docs/` | Documentation only |
| `refactor/` | Internal restructuring, no behavior change |
| `test/` | Test-only changes |

Examples: `feat/session-resize-api`, `fix/pty-close-race`, `chore/bump-actions-checkout`.

Avoid vague names (`updates`, `wip`, `changes`). One logical change per branch when possible.

## Pull requests

- Title: imperative, concise (e.g. "Fix session close race on PTY shutdown").
- Body: **why** the change is needed, what changed, how it was tested.
- Wait for CI (`unit`, `integration`, `analyze`) to pass before requesting review.
- After opening the PR, give the maintainer the URL and wait for browser review — do not auto-merge.

## Exceptions

Direct `main` pushes or admin bypass are only for explicit user-requested hotfixes or repo emergencies — not for normal agent work.
